The slide release notch on the frame and takedown notch have a few tiny burrs. Most of the small light imperfections will easily go unnoticed. The few marks you do see disappear when rotated to a new angle. The gun has no major defects in the finish in our opinion, just honest use. The screw heads are sharp. The markings are clear. Overall, this handgun rates in about Fine - Excellent condition. Mechanics: The action functions correctly. We did not fire this handgun. title: Want To Buy:  Savage/Stevens 87A
postcontent: Made a mistake 2 years ago and I'm trying to make things right. I fell into financial ruin from getting laid off at work and sold most of my rifles to a guy from Strykersville who drove a red Jeep Cherokee. Seemed like a decent guy, I let him borrow a rifle bag and we even kept in touch after the sale. Long story short, when I got back on track I asked him for only the old malfunctioning Savage/Stevens 87A (wouldn't function in semi-auto) and two AR mags from a family member that had sentimental value. I offered three times the value in return, but the guy ghosted me and wound up stealing the rifle bag. I'm certain we'll cross paths eventually.So now I'd like to try and find one similar to it. Like I said it's a Savage/Stevens 87A, sometimes they just go by Savage or Stevens separately. It's a 22 that can fire all 3 variations of that round, but it only works in semi-auto with the 22lr. It's kind of unique in the sense that you can manually lock the bolt to prevent it from firing semi-auto and just use it as a bolt action. The rifle has a very distinct "fish gill" vent on the left side of the receiver. As a fun fact, Springfield made a version of this rifle called the "87M" which the Greatest Generation used in boot camp during WW2 as a trainer before they were handed their M1 Garands. Those 87M's cost around a thousand bucks... I'm just looking for the $150 plain jane 87A. The first image was my 87A that I stupidly sold. If anyone has one that they are willing to part with, or has any leads on where I can find one locally, please let me know. Thank you!

postcontent: A fine set for personal defense or other snakes in the woods.Pietta 1858 w/4.5” barrel, used, no ft sight [New brass bead post, threaded, included]R&D 45LC drop-in conversion cylinder, nice usedHunter brand nylon holsterThis is a work in progress; but, still a bad-boy self-defense shooter. It started life as a 5 1/2” barrel pistol. When I traded for it someone had boogered up the front sight and then wire-welded their 'fix' back in. No way to repair it so that part of the barrel back to behind the loading lever latch had to be removed. So did the loading lever that locks the cylinder pin. I installed a neat spring loaded cylinder pin latch I found on-line [$35]. Makes changing cylinders a breeze for those of us that care about such things.The barrel has been cut to 4.5” and semi-polished at the muzzle. Nice sharp rifling, no rust. Crowning would make it look nicer and a bit more accurate; although, I planned to use it with 45LC #9 shot shells; so, really what difference would it make? Accuracy?  lolStocks are replacements that work fine. Need a bit of fitting around the frame.I have a threaded-post, brass bead for the front sight if you want to have the barrel tapped for it. Just for cosmetic purposes. It would look very cool but be useless as a real sight. Too short. This is a reflex shooter. Point and shoot. The main spring has been lightened to facilitate the draw. Very nice bore with strong rifling. Solid lock-up and hammer drop.The 45 long colt conversion cylinder is in nice condition with some marks of usage. Nice clean chambers and locks up tight in the revolver. Hunter nylon holster is solid and is what it is. Protects the gun. Nice old time personal carry. Just plain nasty close-up and loaded with rat-shot.NO FFL b.s.
